# Painting a Whale Shark in ggplot2, One Layer at a Time

I want to walk through how a short R script conjures something that reads as whale shark skin, and I want to do it in a way that stays useful after the novelty wears off. So rather than admire the output, I will take the thing apart in the order it is assembled and, at each step, point to the one or two knobs that change its behavior. My hope is that by the end you could not only rebuild it but bend it toward a different animal entirely.

The mental model I keep returning to is painting on glass. There are three transparent layers stacked over a fixed rectangle that stands in for the flank: first a colored wash, then a net laid over it, then a scattering of pale dots on top. Everything else in the script is detail about how each of those three layers is made. I will take them in the order the code draws them, since each layer depends on the frame the previous one established.

## The frame and the seed

Everything begins with a frame and a decision about repeatability.

```r
set.seed(42)
n_cols <- 14
n_rows <- 22
```

The seed is what makes the fish reproducible: run the script twice and you get the same animal, because every "random" choice downstream is drawn from the same starting point. (Delete that line, or change the number, and you get a fresh individual on every run, which is the cheapest way I know to generate a whole school from one recipe.) The two dimensions set the proportions of the body, taller than wide, as a flank tends to be. Bump `n_rows` up and the pattern elongates; bring the two numbers closer together and it squares off toward a tile.

## The color wash underneath

With the frame set, the first thing drawn is the color underneath everything else. I lay down a fine grid of little tiles and give each tile a single number that describes where it sits.

```r
bg$rad  <- sqrt(((bg$x-cx)/cx)^2 + ((bg$y-cy)/cy)^2)
bg$diag <- (bg$x+bg$y)/(n_cols+n_rows)
bg$t    <- pmin(1, 0.55*bg$rad + 0.45*bg$diag)
```

Here `rad` measures how far each tile sits from the center and `diag` is a sweep from one corner to the opposite one. The line that matters is the third, where I blend the two. You can read `0.55*bg$rad + 0.45*bg$diag` as "mostly a glow radiating out from the middle, with a bit of corner-to-corner lean mixed in." That single number `t` then indexes into a three-stop color ramp, so a low value comes out deep navy and a high value comes out pale blue:

```r
scale_fill_gradientn(colours = c(deep, mid, edge))
```

In other words, the sense of a rounded, lit surface (rather than a flat swatch) is not drawn; it falls out of a distance calculation fed through a ramp. It follows that this is exactly the layer to attack if what you want next is a richer color gradient. You can swap the three hex stops for a longer vector of colors, or replace `bg$t` with something that varies head-to-tail instead of center-out, for instance `bg$y / n_rows`. Change the recipe for `t`, and the whole body re-tints without your ever touching the net or the dots.

## The net, whose weight is accumulated rather than drawn

With the wash down, the middle layer is the pale net, the reticulation. This is the layer I would ask you to read slowly, because its texture is not so much drawn as accumulated, and that is the part most people find surprising.

Each line begins as a straight run that I then bend:

```r
base_disp <- wobble*sin(runif(1,.4,.9)*along + runif(1,0,6.28)) +
             rnorm(length(along), 0, 0.03)
```

That is a slow sine wave, its frequency picked at random per line (hence the `runif`), plus a little per-point noise, so that no line ever comes out mechanically straight. Turn `wobble` up and the net goes seasick; turn it toward zero and you approach graph paper. But the character of the stroke, its weight and its grain, comes from the loop that follows:

```r
k <- sample(seq_len(max_copies), 1)
do.call(rbind, lapply(seq_len(k), function(cc) {
  jx <- jit*sin(runif(1,1,3)*along+runif(1,0,6.28)) + rnorm(length(along),0,jit*0.3)
  jy <- jit*sin(runif(1,1,3)*along+runif(1,0,6.28)) + rnorm(length(along),0,jit*0.3)
  data.frame(grp=paste0(id,"_",cc), x=bx+jx, y=by+jy)
}))
```

Here is the trick worth dwelling on. I draw each line not once but `k` times, a random count up to `max_copies`, nudging every copy by a minuscule `jit` in both directions, and I render each copy at low opacity through `line_alpha`. It follows that width and weight are emergent: where the faint copies pile up, the stroke reads solid and dark; where they drift apart, it softens and spreads; and a line that happened to draw only once stays thin and ghostly. I never compute a line's width directly. Both its thickness and its hand-inked grain come out of nothing but repetition and a small random offset.

That gives you three fairly independent dials on the net's personality. `max_copies` controls how heavy and uneven the lines get, since more copies mean a bolder, more variable stroke. `jit` controls how far the copies splay, so a larger jitter frays the line into something brushy (which is exactly the dial I turned *down* when the lines were shouting over the dots). And `line_alpha` sets how much each copy contributes, so lowering it keeps even a ten-copy line delicate. To make this concrete: set `max_copies <- 1` and `jit <- 0` and you get clean, single-stroke reticulation, almost technical; set `max_copies <- 10` and `jit <- 0.05` and you get something closer to ink bleeding on wet paper. Same mechanism, opposite temperaments.

## The dots, and the one field that governs them

Now the top layer, the dots, which is where most of the recent tuning went. It opens by choosing where the head sits:

```r
head_xy <- switch(head_quadrant,
  "top-left"  = c(n_cols*0.25, n_rows*0.75),
  ... )
```

and then computes the single quantity that everything else hangs on:

```r
d <- sqrt((cells$cx-head_x)^2 + (cells$cy-head_y)^2)
cells$h <- exp(-(d/reach_cells)^2)      # 1 at head, ->0 away
```

That `h` is what I call the head-ness field: a Gaussian bump worth one right at the head and fading smoothly to zero as you move off it, with `reach_cells` setting its half-width. Recall that this parameter was the whole fix for the "I cannot see a density peak" problem. When the half-width was around twelve cells, the bump smeared across the entire plot and no peak was visible; a gentle ramp spread over an entire field is invisible almost by definition, because the eye localizes a hotspot by contrast against its neighborhood. Bring it down to five and the bump sits in a legible blob; bring it down to three and the head becomes a tight, unmistakable knot of spots.

The reason I bothered to route everything through that one field is that it lets me drive two traits from it at once, and in opposite directions:

```r
cells$lam   <- lam_far  + (lam_head  - lam_far ) * cells$h   # dense at head
cells$n     <- rpois(nrow(cells), cells$lam)
cells$smean <- size_far + (size_head - size_far) * cells$h   # small at head
```

The first line makes the expected count rise with `h`; the third makes the mean size fall with it. So the crowded region and the small-dot region are guaranteed to be the same place, which is the coupling you can see in a real animal: many fine spots at the head, fewer and coarser ones toward the tail. Note the `rpois`: the count in a cell is a random draw around the expectation `lam`, not the expectation itself, which is what keeps the field irregular instead of looking stamped. The `lam_head` and `lam_far` pair is your density contrast, and the `size_head` and `size_far` pair is your size contrast; widen either gap for a more dramatic gradient, close it for a more even coat. (And if you ever wanted to break the coupling, letting size vary independently of density the way some individuals are simply more uniform than others, you would compute `smean` from something other than `h`, and the two traits would go their separate ways. The architecture does not force the marriage; it just makes it convenient.)

Each cell's dots are then scattered off their grid point and given their spread:

```r
size  = pmax(0.02, cells$smean[i] * runif(k, 1-size_jit, 1+size_jit)),
alpha = runif(k, 0.45, 1.00)
```

Here `size_jit` is the small per-dot wobble around the cell's mean, and it earns its keep precisely by being small. Recall that when this was a wild multiplier, running from 0.6 to 1.35, the within-cell size noise was wider than the head-to-tail signal, so a large dot near the head and a small dot far away overlapped, and the eye dutifully reported "all the same size." Keep the jitter modest and the gradient survives contact with the noise. The `alpha` line simply gives each dot its own transparency for a sense of depth, though you could tie it to `h` instead and make the head not only denser but brighter, if that ever appeals.

## Assembly

The assembly itself is almost anticlimactic, because by now the hard thinking already lives in the data rather than in the plotting:

```r
p <- ggplot() +
  geom_raster(...) + scale_fill_gradientn(...) +   # wash
  geom_path(...) +                                  # net
  geom_point(...) +                                 # dots
  coord_fixed(...) + theme_void()
```

The layers stack in the order written, wash then net then dots on top; `coord_fixed` locks the aspect ratio so the proportions cannot stretch; and `theme_void` strips the axes and gridlines so that nothing but the pattern shows. One small lever hides here: if you ever want the dots to sit under the net rather than over it, you swap the order of those two `geom_` lines, and the whole feel shifts from spots-on-a-net to a-net-over-spots.

## What the recipe really is

So the pattern is less a picture than a small generative recipe, and it rewards tinkering at three levels, each with its own character. The frame and the palette decide the body's shape and its color. The trio of copy count, jitter, and opacity decides the weight and texture of the net. And the head-ness field decides where the spots crowd and how their size trades off against their number. Change where the head sits and how quickly `h` fades, and, como quien no quiere la cosa, the entire animal reorganizes itself around that one choice.

The color gradient is the piece I have not yet built, and it is the natural next move: the wash already reduces the whole background to a single number `t`, so a richer palette is a change of ramp rather than a change of machinery. That, I suspect, is where this goes next.

---

## Appendix: the complete script

```r
library(ggplot2)

set.seed(42)

# ---- parameters -------------------------------------------------------------
n_cols   <- 14
n_rows   <- 22
wobble   <- 0.14    # slightly straighter reticulation than before

# lines: redrawn with jitter, but de-frayed (fewer copies, tighter jitter)
max_copies <- 6
jit        <- 0.020
line_alpha <- 0.16
line_w     <- 0.35

# ONE head-ness field h in [0,1] drives BOTH count and size, so the density
# peak and the small-dot region are the same place, by construction.
head_quadrant <- "top-left"   # top-left | top-right | bottom-left | bottom-right
reach_cells <- 5.0   # TIGHT: half-width of the hotspot in cells (was ~12)
lam_head <- 5.0      # dots/cell at the head (dense)
lam_far  <- 0.60     # dots/cell far away (sparse but not barren)
size_head <- 0.045   # dot size at the head (small)
size_far  <- 0.40    # dot size far away (large)
size_jit  <- 0.14    # +/- fraction of per-dot size noise (was 0.6..1.35 = huge)

deep <- "#0b2f57"; mid <- "#12557f"; edge <- "#4ba3c9"; pale <- "#dbeff5"

# ---- background gradient ----------------------------------------------------
gres <- 260
bg <- expand.grid(x = seq(0, n_cols, length.out = gres),
                  y = seq(0, n_rows, length.out = gres))
cx <- n_cols/2; cy <- n_rows/2
bg$rad  <- sqrt(((bg$x-cx)/cx)^2 + ((bg$y-cy)/cy)^2)
bg$diag <- (bg$x+bg$y)/(n_cols+n_rows)
bg$t    <- pmin(1, 0.55*bg$rad + 0.45*bg$diag)

# ---- lines: jittered copies, de-frayed --------------------------------------
build_line_copies <- function(id, fixed, along, orient) {
  base_disp <- wobble*sin(runif(1,.4,.9)*along + runif(1,0,6.28)) + rnorm(length(along),0,0.03)
  if (orient=="v") { bx <- fixed+base_disp; by <- along } else { bx <- along; by <- fixed+base_disp }
  k <- sample(seq_len(max_copies), 1)
  do.call(rbind, lapply(seq_len(k), function(cc) {
    jx <- jit*sin(runif(1,1,3)*along+runif(1,0,6.28)) + rnorm(length(along),0,jit*0.3)
    jy <- jit*sin(runif(1,1,3)*along+runif(1,0,6.28)) + rnorm(length(along),0,jit*0.3)
    data.frame(grp=paste0(id,"_",cc), x=bx+jx, y=by+jy)
  }))
}
along_y <- seq(0, n_rows, length.out = 200)
along_x <- seq(0, n_cols, length.out = 200)
lines_df <- rbind(
  do.call(rbind, lapply(0:n_cols, function(i) build_line_copies(paste0("v",i), i, along_y, "v"))),
  do.call(rbind, lapply(0:n_rows, function(j) build_line_copies(paste0("h",j), j, along_x, "h")))
)

# ---- dots: single head-ness field drives count AND size ---------------------
head_xy <- switch(head_quadrant,
  "top-left"     = c(n_cols*0.25, n_rows*0.75),
  "top-right"    = c(n_cols*0.75, n_rows*0.75),
  "bottom-left"  = c(n_cols*0.25, n_rows*0.25),
  "bottom-right" = c(n_cols*0.75, n_rows*0.25))
head_x <- head_xy[1]; head_y <- head_xy[2]

cells <- expand.grid(cx = seq(0.5, n_cols-0.5, by=1),
                     cy = seq(0.5, n_rows-0.5, by=1))
d <- sqrt((cells$cx-head_x)^2 + (cells$cy-head_y)^2)
cells$h <- exp(-(d/reach_cells)^2)                       # 1 at head, ->0 away

cells$lam   <- lam_far  + (lam_head  - lam_far ) * cells$h        # dense at head
cells$n     <- rpois(nrow(cells), cells$lam)
cells$smean <- size_far + (size_head - size_far) * cells$h        # small at head

dots <- do.call(rbind, lapply(which(cells$n > 0), function(i) {
  k <- cells$n[i]
  data.frame(
    x = cells$cx[i] + runif(k, -0.42, 0.42),
    y = cells$cy[i] + runif(k, -0.42, 0.42),
    size  = pmax(0.02, cells$smean[i] * runif(k, 1-size_jit, 1+size_jit)),
    alpha = runif(k, 0.45, 1.00)
  )
}))

# ---- plot -------------------------------------------------------------------
p <- ggplot() +
  geom_raster(data=bg, aes(x,y,fill=t)) +
  scale_fill_gradientn(colours=c(deep,mid,edge)) +
  geom_path(data=lines_df, aes(x,y,group=grp), colour=pale, alpha=line_alpha, linewidth=line_w) +
  geom_point(data=dots, aes(x,y,size=size,alpha=alpha), colour=pale) +
  scale_size_identity() + scale_alpha_identity() +
  coord_fixed(xlim=c(0,n_cols), ylim=c(0,n_rows), expand=FALSE) +
  theme_void() +
  theme(legend.position="none", plot.background=element_rect(fill=deep, colour=NA))

ggsave("whaleshark_pattern.png", p, width=5, height=7.5, dpi=130)
```